definition.val: A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.
Temporal interval that defines rat life from prenatal stage until late adult stage.

comments: Vaginal plug normally persists 12 - 24 hours and may lasts as long as 48 hours (see http://web.jhu.edu/animalcare/procedures/rat.html).

definition.val: Prenatal stage that starts with fertilization and ends with the fully formed embryo.

comments: Rat birth occurs at the 22nd day of development (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Development_Stages).

definition.val: Prenatal stage that starts with fertilization and ends with a fully formed embryo, before undergoing last development during the fetal stage.

comments: This stage covers the first 16 days of the embryonic development, from Standard Witschi Stage 1 until Standard Witschi Stage 33 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline), we treat fetus as a separate stage.

definition.val: Embryonic stage that starts with the one-cell zygote in the oviduct and ends with the free blastocyst in the uterus.

comments: This stage covers the first 5 days of the embryonic development, from Standard Witschi Stage 1 up to 7 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline). Refers to human Carnegie stage 1 up to 4 (see http://books.google.ch/books?id=yr1ZRO8H0ysC&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false "Table 12.17, p.510")

definition.val: Embryonic stage defined by complex and coordinated series of cellular movements that occurs at the end of cleavage.

comments: This stage covers the blastocyst uterus implantation period, from Standard Witschi Stage 8 up to 12 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline). Refers to human Carnegie stage 4 up to 6 (see http://books.google.ch/books?id=yr1ZRO8H0ysC&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false "Table 12.17, p.510")

definition.val: Embryonic stage during which the primitive streak appears.

comments: This stage corresponds to Standard Witschi Stage 12 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline). Refers to human Carnegie stage 6 up to 7 (see http://books.google.ch/books?id=yr1ZRO8H0ysC&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false "Table 12.17, p.510")

definition.val: Embryonic stage defined by formation of a tube from the flat layer of ectodermal cells known as the neural plate.

comments: This stage corresponds to Standard Witschi Stage 13 up to 17 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline). Refers to human Carnegie stage 7 up to 12 (see http://books.google.ch/books?id=yr1ZRO8H0ysC&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false "Table 12.17, p.510")

definition.val: Embryonic stage during which somites 26-28(upper lumbar) up to somites 39-40(caudal) appear.

comments: This stage corresponds to Standard Witschi Stage 18 up to 24 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline). Refers to human Carnegie stage 12 up to 13 (see http://books.google.ch/books?id=yr1ZRO8H0ysC&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false "Table 12.17, p.510")

definition.val: Embryonic stage during which somites 41-42(caudal) appear and tail and allantoic stalk rise to the placenta.

comments: This stage corresponds to Standard Witschi Stage 25 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline). Refers to human Carnegie stage 14 (see http://books.google.ch/books?id=yr1ZRO8H0ysC&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false "Table 12.17, p.510")

definition.val: Embryonic stage during which somites 43-45 (caudal) up to somite 65 (usually this is last caudal) appear.

comments: This stage corresponds to Standard Witschi Stage 26 up to 33 (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline). Refers to human Carnegie stage 15 up to 22 (see http://books.google.ch/books?id=yr1ZRO8H0ysC&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false "Table 12.17, p.510")

definition.val: Prenatal stage that starts with the fully formed embryo and ends at birth.

comments: This stage corresponds to Standard Witschi Stage 34 up to 35 ante-natal (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline). Refers to the human fetal period (Carnegie stage 23 and later) (see http://books.google.ch/books?id=yr1ZRO8H0ysC&printsec=frontcover&hl=fr#v=onepage&q&f=false "Table 12.17, p.510")

definition.val: Rat developmental stage that covers the period from birth until about 10 weeks old, when individuals usually reach sexual maturity.

comments: Rats reach sexual maturity by 70 days of age for male and 90 days of age for female (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Rattus_norvegicus).

definition.val: Immature stage that covers the period from birth until 16 days of age.

comments: This stage describes the post-natal period when the fetus becomes a breathing and suckling nestling during the first 16 days (22 to 38 days total age), while eyelids remain sealed and external ear ducts are plugged with periderm (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline).

definition.val: Immature stage that refers to a rat which is over 2 weeks and under 10 weeks old.

comments: This stage starts with the period at which periderm seals of ears and eyelids vanish, and ends when the rat becomes sexually mature (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline and http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Rattus_norvegicus).

definition.val: Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 10 weeks old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 10 and under 11 weeks old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 11 and under 12 weeks old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 3 and under 4 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 4 and under 7 months old.

comments: This stage was created to match age provided by GEO Rat expression data.

definition.val: Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 4 and under 5 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 5 and under 6 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 6 and under 7 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 7 and under 8 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 8 and under 9 months old.

Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 14 and under 15 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 15 and under 16 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 16 and under 17 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 17 and under 18 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 18 and under 19 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 19 and under 20 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 20 and under 21 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 21 and under 22 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 22 and under 23 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 23 and under 24 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 24 and under 27 months old.

comments: This stage was created to match age provided by GEO Rat expression data.

definition.val: Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 24 and under 25 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 25 and under 26 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 26 and under 27 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 27 and under 28 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 28 and under 29 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 29 and under 30 months old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 30 and under 31 months old.
Embryonic stage defined by one-cell embryo (in oviduct)

comments: Starts the rat embroynic development. Occurs during the first day after fertilization (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Rat_Development_Stages).

definition.val: Embryonic stage consisting of division of cells in the early embryo.

comments: The different cells derived from cleavage are called blastomeres and form a compact mass called the morula. Cleavage ends with the formation of the blastula.

definition.val: Cleavage stage defined by 2-cells embryo (in oviduct)

comments: This stage occurs during the second day after fertilization (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Rat_Development_Stages).

definition.val: Cleavage stage defined by 4-cells embryo (in oviduct)

comments: This stage occurs during the third day of rat development (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Rat_Development_Stages).

definition.val: Cleavage stage defined by an embryo of 8-12 cells (in oviduct)

comments: This stage occurs during the third day of rat development (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Rat_Development_Stages).

definition.val: Cleavage stage defined by the morula (in oviduct)

comments: This stage occurs during the third day of rat development (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Rat_Development_Stages).

definition.val: Embryonic stage that is an early stage of embryonic development in animals and is produced by cleavage of a fertilized ovum, with formation of a central fluid-filled cavity called the blastocoel.

comments: Covers Witschi stages 6 and 7, during days 4 and 5 of the embryonic development, when blastocyst is still free in the uterus (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Rat_Timeline#Day_4).

definition.val: Embryonic stage at which the ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm develop into the internal organs of the organism.
Rat developmental stage that covers the period from birth until weaning.

comments: Weaning occurs at about 25 days of age (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline).

definition.val: Immature stage that refers to a rat which is over 2 weeks and still not weaned.

comments: This stage starts with the period at which periderm seals of ears and eyelids vanish, and ends at weaning, at about 25 days of age (see http://php.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Rat_Timeline and http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Rattus_norvegicus).

definition.val: Immature stage that refers to a weaned rat which is under 10 weeks old.
Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 10 weeks old, and under 18 months old.

comments: Senescence in rat starts at about 19 months old (see https://www.criver.com/products-services/discovery-services/pharmacology-studies/neuroscience-models-assays/alzheimers-disease-studies/aged-rats-and-mice-cognitive-decline?region=3696)

definition.val: Rat developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult rat, which is over 18 months old.
Rat developmental stage that covers the period from birth until late adulthood.

Count of number of days intervening between the end of the stage and the time of coitum, defined as the time the vaginal plug is found. Note that the vaginal plug persists for 16-24 hours and may lasts as long as 48 hours.

comments: This is a shortcut annotation that can be expanded to an OWL axiom, or to a set of OWL axioms. The exact translation has yet to be determined, and may be application-dependent.

definition.val: Count of number of months intervening between the end of the stage and the time of birth according to a reference model. Note that the first month of post-birth development has the value of 1 for this property, and the period during which the organism is one month old has the value 2

comments: This is a shortcut annotation that can be expanded to an OWL axiom, or to a set of OWL axioms. The exact translation has yet to be determined, and may be application-dependent.

definition.val: Count of number of weeks intervening between the end of the stage and the time of birth according to a reference model. Note that the first week of post-birth development has the value of 1 for this property, and the period during which the rat is one week old has the value 2

comments: This is a shortcut annotation that can be expanded to an OWL axiom, or to a set of OWL axioms. The exact translation has yet to be determined, and may be application-dependent.

Subset consisting of classes describing highly granular developmental stages (for instance, '23-year-old'). Such stages might be useful for annotation purpose, but might be folded into less granular parents for display purpose.
Used to associate a measurement property (e.g. days post fertilization) with a unit (e.g. days)

definition.val: Count of number of days intervening between the start of the stage and the time of coitum, defined as the time the vaginal plug is found. Note that the vaginal plug persists for 16-24 hours and may lasts as long as 48 hours.

comments: This is a shortcut annotation that can be expanded to an OWL axiom, or to a set of OWL axioms. The exact translation has yet to be determined, and may be application-dependent.

definition.val: Count of number of days intervening between the start of the stage and the time of fertilization according to a reference model. Note that the first day of development has the value of 0 for this property.

comments: This is a shortcut annotation that can be expanded to an OWL axiom, or to a set of OWL axioms. The exact translation has yet to be determined, and may be application-dependent.

comments: This is a shortcut annotation that can be expanded to an OWL axiom, or to a set of OWL axioms. The exact translation has yet to be determined, and may be application-dependent.

definition.val: Count of number of weeks intervening between the start of the stage and the time of birth according to a reference model. Note that the first week of post-birth development has the value of 0 for this property, and the period during which the rat is one week old has the value 1.
